41. Monolithic:
Tightly coupled and run as a single service. All are interconnected service
Simple to develop and deploy (good for small applications).
Microservice:
A collection of small, independent services that communicate with each other over web protocols like rest apis
Good for large, scalable systems.
Each service has its own codebase and can be deployed independently.
Advantage: failure in one service doesn’t crash the whole system

42. Steps to Deploy FastAPI on AWS EC2 (Ubuntu)
Create an EC2 instance with Ubuntu server.
Add firewall rules to allow TCP port 22 (SSH) and port 8000 (FastAPI default).
Allow external access to ports 22, 8000, and your database port.
Clone the project to the server using Git.
Create a start.sh file that installs pip requirements and runs the application server.
Create a virtual environment.
Install Gunicorn.
Create a service file and link it to start.sh.
Use systemctl to enable the .service file.
Use systemctl to start the service.
Install Nginx (sudo apt install nginx).
Create an Nginx config file to set up reverse proxy:
Forward requests from port 88 (or 80/443 for production)
Point to your FastAPI app running on port 8000
Add your server’s IP address or domain name

43.What is a Context Manager?
A context manager in FastAPI is a way to run some code before your app starts and after your app stops.
Using @asynccontextmanager decorator in function 
It’s often used for things like:
Connecting to a database
Loading initial (seed) data
Cleaning up resources when the app shuts down

44. RestAPI?
send http request from client to server and then get a response back.
Client → Http Request → Server → Response → Client

45. What is a Router in FastAPI?
A router in FastAPI is a way to organize your API endpoints.
Instead of writing all routes in one file, you can split them into different routers (like user routes, product routes, etc.) and then include them in your main app.

