60. CORS stands for Cross‑Origin Resource Sharing.
It’s a browser security mechanism that allows a web application running on 
one origin (domain, protocol, or port) to request resources from another origin
When the application is running, the backend communicates with the frontend. At that time, we were getting CORS errors.
To fix this, we integrated CORS middleware into the app’s middleware settings.
In the development environment, we used allow_origins="*" to permit all domains.
In production, we restricted allow_origins to only the frontend URL and IP address.


BRD - Business Requirements Document, focusing on why a project is needed and its high-level business goals.
SRS - Software Requirements Specification, Provides functional/non-functional requirements (detailing how the system will work to meet those needs)

Roles & Responsibilities (Interview Version)
I lead backend development using Python FastAPI and PostgreSQL, focusing on database design and REST API implementation.

I integrate third‑party tools like Redmine and GitLab via APIs, building a two‑way synchronization system to keep external tools and our main database aligned.

I ensure security and compliance by implementing Azure AD Single Sign‑On, JWT authentication, and role‑based access control in line with ASPICE standards.

I automate recurring tasks with APScheduler, such as syncing Redmine/GitLab data and handling checklist approvals.

I actively participate in daily Scrum meetings, translating BRD/SRS requirements into technical solutions and collaborating with designers.

I mentor junior developers, guiding them on best practices, code reviews, and aligning their work with project standards.
